{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609052"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16082"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16082"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.03,0.19,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115195"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97203"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"1490"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7033"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20957"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115195"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe aetiology of ectopic pregnancy involves multiple factors. Altered fallopian tube motility is a significant contributing factor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most commonly contributes to altered tubal motility resulting in ectopic pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pelvic inflammatory disease","Current use of combined oral contraceptives","Previous tubal ligation surgery","In utero exposure to diethylstilbestrol","Current intrauterine device use"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic inflammatory disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of altered tubal motility leading to ectopic pregnancy. The infection and subsequent inflammation damages the ciliated epithelium of the fallopian tubes, impairs smooth muscle function, and can cause scarring that distorts the tubal anatomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECurrent use of combined oral contraceptives\u003C/strong\u003E reduces the risk of ectopic pregnancy by preventing ovulation. \u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious tubal ligation surgery\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to ectopic pregnancy if the procedure fails, but does not primarily affect tubal motility. \u003Cstrong\u003EIn utero exposure to diethylstilbestrol\u003C/strong\u003E causes structural abnormalities of the reproductive tract but is now very rare. \u003Cstrong\u003ECurrent intrauterine device use\u003C/strong\u003E may increase the relative risk of ectopic pregnancy if conception occurs, but does not directly affect tubal motility. The damage to tubal epithelium from infection impairs the transport of the embryo, increasing the risk of tubal implantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prior pelvic inflammatory disease is the most significant risk factor for ectopic pregnancy due to tubal scarring and altered ciliary function.","Damage to fallopian tube ciliated epithelium impairs embryo transport and increases risk of implantation within the tube."],"references":["Trent M. Pelvic inflammatory disease. Pediatr Rev. 2013 Apr;34(4):163-72. doi: 10.1542/pir.34-4-163. Erratum in: Pediatr Rev. 2013 Oct;34(10):456. PMID: 23547062; PMCID: PMC4530285.","He D, Wang T, Ren W. Global burden of pelvic inflammatory disease and ectopic pregnancy from 1990 to 2019. BMC Public Health. 2023 Oct 2;23(1):1894. doi: 10.1186/s12889-023-16663-y. PMID: 37784046; PMCID: PMC10544469.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97203"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97203"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T09:41:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T09:42:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115195"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"